d","Blair, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Blare","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Blaise   2. See also   Blaize   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Blaise","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Dominique, Edrice, Evens, Guerline, Jean-Claude, Kettly, Marthe, Monique, Murielle, Serge, Yves.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the French personal name <i>Blaise</i>, from Latin   Blasius  . Compare   Blaize   1.","Scottish (Ayrshire and Bute): variant of   Blaize   2."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William De Blare of that Ilk, 3rd Lord of Blair was born about 1180, in Ayrshire, Scotland as the son of Sir William Francis De Blare, 2nd Lord of Blair. He married Eleanor about 1228, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1232, in his hometown, at the age of 54."},"et":{"about 1180–about 1232":"umbes 1180–umbes 1232","1180–1232":"1180–1232","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1225–1296":"1225–1296","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","about 1228":"umbes 1228","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1232":"1232","about 1225":"umbes 1225","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","about 1232":"umbes 1232","1160":"1160","about 1230":"umbes 1230","1180":"1180","Ayrshire, Kingdom of Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Blair, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1180–about 1232":"noin 1180–noin 1232","1180–1232":"1180–1232","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1225–1296":"1225–1296","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","about 1228":"noin 1228","about 1180":"noin 1180","1232":"1232","about 1225":"noin 1225","1230":"1230","1296":"1296","about 1232":"noin 1232","1160":"1160","about 1230":"noin 1230","1180":"1180","Ayrshire, Kingdom of Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Blair, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1180–about 1232":"environ 1180–environ 1232","1180–1232":"1180–1232","1205–Female":"1205–Décédée","1225–1296":"1225–1296","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","1160–Male":"1160–Décédé","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","about 1228":"environ 1228","about 1180":"environ 1180","1232":"1232","about 1225":"environ 1225","1